quran[70]{c,v,t}:
  69,1,The Inevitable Hour
  69,2,What is the Inevitable Hour
  69,3,And what will make you realize what the Inevitable Hour is
  69,4,The tribes of Thamud and 'Ad denied that disaster would strike them
  69,5,the Thamud were destroyed by a terrible storm of thunder and lightning
  69,6,and the 'Ad were destroyed by a furious wind
  69,7,"which God let loose against them for seven nights and eight days unremittingly, so that you could have seen its people lying prostrate as though they were the hollow trunks of palm-trees which had fallen down"
  69,8,Do you see any vestige left of them now
  69,9,Pharoah and those before him and the inhabitants of the overthrown cities persistently committed grave sins
  69,10,"They defied their Lord's messenger, so He seized them with an ever-tightening grip"
  69,11,"But We bore you away in the Ark, when the waters rose high"
  69,12,so that We might make it a reminder for you and so that attentive ears might retain it
  69,13,When a single blast is blown on the trumpet
  69,14,and the earth and the mountains are lifted up and then crushed with a single blow
  69,15,on that Day the Great Event will come to pass
  69,16,"And the sky will be rent asunder, for on that Day it will be so frail"
  69,17,"The angels will appear by its sides and, on that Day, eight [angels] will bear your Lord's throne above them"
  69,18,On that Day you will be brought to judgement and none of your secrets will remain hidden
  69,19,"Then he who is given his record in his right hand will exclaim, \"Here is my record, read it"
  69,20,"Surely, I knew that I should meet my reckoning"
  69,21,so he will live in a state of Bliss
  69,22,in a lofty garden
  69,23,with clusters of fruit within easy reach
  69,24,"We shall say to him, \"Eat and drink joyfully as a reward for the good deeds you did in days gone by"
  69,25,"But he who is given his record in his left hand will say, \"If only I had never been given my Record"
  69,26,and knew nothing of my reckoning
  69,27,How I wish my death had ended all
  69,28,My wealth has been of no use to me
  69,29,I am bereft of power
  69,30,Seize him and fetter him
  69,31,and then let him enter Hell
  69,32,Then fasten him with a chain seventy cubits long
  69,33,for he did not believe in Almighty God
  69,34,nor did he feel any urge to feed the needy
  69,35,so today he has no friend here
  69,36,and the only food he has is filth
  69,37,which no one will eat except the sinners
  69,38,"But nay, I swear by all that you can see"
  69,39,as well as all that you cannot see
  69,40,"most surely, this is the word brought by a noble messenger"
  69,41,it is not the word of a poet -- how little you believe
  69,42,Nor is it the word of a soothsayer -- how little you reflect
  69,43,It is a revelation sent down by the Sustainer of the Universe
  69,44,if he had invented any lies about Us
  69,45,We would indeed have seized him by his right hand
  69,46,and would indeed have cut his life-vein
  69,47,and none of you could have held Us off from him
  69,48,And surely it is an admonition to the God-fearing
  69,49,We know very well that there are some among you who reject Our signs
  69,50,it will be a source of bitter regret for those who deny the truth
  69,51,it is the indubitable truth
  69,52,"So glorify the name of your Lord, the Almighty"
  70,1,A doubter once demanded that punishment be immediately meted out
  70,2,to those who deny the truth. No power can hinder God
  70,3,from punishing them. He is the Lord of the Ascending Stairways
  70,4,by which the angels and the Spirit will ascend to Him in one Day which will last for fifty thousand years
  70,5,"Therefore, [O believers] behave with seemly patience"
  70,6,"They see it [the Day of Judgement] to be far off"
  70,7,but We see it near at hand
  70,8,On that Day the heavens shall become like molten brass
  70,9,and the mountains will become like tufts of wool
  70,10,and no friend will ask about his friend
  70,11,though they shall be within sight of each other. The guilty one will gladly ransom himself from the torment of that Day by sacrificing his own children
  70,12,"his wife, his brother"
  70,13,and his kinsfolk who gave him shelter
  70,14,"and all the people of the earth, if that could deliver him"
  70,15,But no! There is a raging blaze
  70,16,stripping away his skin
  70,17,"and it will claim all those who turned their backs [on the true faith] and turned away [from the truth]"
  70,18,and amassed wealth and hoarded it